SIMPLE: evil
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evil
<hw>E*vil</hw> <pr>(⟦emac⟧"v'l)</pr> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>evel</ets>, <ets>evil</ets>, <ets>ifel</ets>, <ets>uvel</ets>, AS.
<ets>yfel</ets>; akin to OFries, <ets>evel</ets>, D. <ets>euvel</ets>,
OS. & OHG. <ets>ubil</ets>, G. <ets>⟦uum⟧bel</ets>, Goth.
<ets>ubils</ets>, and perh. to E. <ets>over</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Having qualities tending to injury and mischief; having a nature or
properties which tend to badness; mischievous; not good; worthless or
deleterious; poor; <as>as, an <ex>evil</ex> beast; and <ex>evil</ex>
plant; an <ex>evil</ex> crop.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A good tree can not bring forth <qex>evil</qex> fruit.</q>
<rj><qau>Matt. vii. 18.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having or exhibiting bad moral qualities; morally
corrupt; wicked; wrong; vicious; <as>as, <ex>evil</ex> conduct,
thoughts, heart, words, and the like</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ah, what a sign it is of <qex>evil</qex> life,⟦br⟧
When death's approach is seen so terrible.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Producing or threatening sorrow, distress, injury,
or calamity; unpropitious; calamitous; <as>as, <ex>evil</ex> tidings;
<ex>evil</ex> arrows; <ex>evil</ex> days.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Because he hath brought up an <qex>evil</qex> name upon a virgin
of Israel.</q> <rj><qau>Deut. xxii. 19.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The owl shrieked at thy birth -- an <qex>evil</qex> sign.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Evil</qex> news rides post, while good news baits.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><col><b>Evil eye</b></col>, <cd>an eye which inflicts injury by
some magical or fascinating influence. It is still believed by the
ignorant and superstitious that some persons have the supernatural power
of injuring by a look.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It almost led him to believe in the <qex>evil eye</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>J. H. Newman.</qau></rj></p>

<p>-- <col><b>Evil speaking</b></col>, <cd>speaking ill of others;
calumny; censoriousness.</cd> -- <col><b>The evil one</b></col>, <cd>the
Devil; Satan.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Evil</xex> is sometimes written as the first part
of a compound (with or without a hyphen). In many cases the compounding
need not be insisted on. Examples: <xex>Evil</xex> doer or
<xex>evil</xex>doer, <xex>evil</xex> speaking or
<xex>evil</xex>-speaking, <xex>evil</xex> worker, <xex>evil</xex>
wishing, <xex>evil</xex>-hearted, <xex>evil</xex>-minded.</note></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Mischieveous; pernicious; injurious; hurtful;
destructive; wicked; sinful; bad; corrupt; perverse; wrong; vicious;
calamitous.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 518 bad typing! --></p>

<p><ent>Evil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Evil
<hw>E"vil</hw> <pr>(⟦emac⟧"v'l)</pr> <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Anything which impairs the happiness of a being or deprives a being
of any good; anything which causes suffering of any kind to sentient
beings; injury; mischief; harm; -- opposed to <ant>good</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Evils</qex> which our own misdeeds have wrought.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>evil</qex> that men do lives after them.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Moral badness, or the deviation of a moral being
from the principles of virtue imposed by conscience, or by the will of
the Supreme Being, or by the principles of a lawful human authority;
disposition to do wrong; moral offense; wickedness; depravity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The heart of the sons of men is full of <qex>evil</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Eccl. ix. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>malady or disease; especially in the phrase
<stype>king's evil</stype>, the scrofula.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He [Edward the Confessor] was the first that touched for the
<qex>evil</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evil</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Evil
<hw>E"vil</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In an evil manner; not well; ill;
badly; unhappily; injuriously; unkindly.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It went <qex>evil</qex> with his house.</q> <rj><qau>1 Chron. vii.
23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Egyptians <qex>evil</qex> entreated us, and affected us.</q>
<rj><qau>Deut. xxvi. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>evildoer</ent>⟦br⟧
